Create a function to show the above dataframe for each variable

In [7]:
def dist_df(var):
    df_var = train[[var,'loan_default']].groupby(var)['loan_default'].agg(['count','sum']).reset_index()
    df_var.columns = [var,'X_counts','Y_counts']
    df_var['X_pcnt'] = df_var['X_counts'] / sum(df_var['X_counts'])
    df_var['Y_by_X_pcnt'] = df_var['Y_counts'] / df_var['X_counts']
    return df_var

Create a function to loop through plots

In [10]:
def plot_X_and_Y(var):
    import matplotlib
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import numpy as np
    
    ind = dist_df(var)[var].astype(str)
    x_count = dist_df(var)['X_pcnt']
    y_by_x = dist_df(var)['Y_by_X_pcnt']
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,4))
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.bar(ind, x_count)
    plt.xlabel(var)
    plt.ylabel('X_pcnt')
    plt.xticks(ind, rotation=45)
    plt.title(var + ' Distribution')

    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.plot(ind, y_by_x, color='r')
    plt.xlabel(var)
    plt.ylabel('Y_by_X_pcnt')
    plt.xticks(ind, rotation=45)
    plt.title('Y_by_X_pcnt Distribution')
    plt.show()
In [11]:
for n in var_list_ap:
    plot_X_and_Y(n)

Section 2. Feature Engineering¶

  • Use Weight of Evidence encoding
  • The goal of such transformation is to get the maximum difference among the binned categories relating to the target variable.
  • It counts the number of responders and non-responders in each binned categories, then assigns a numeric value to each of the binned categories.

WoE formula: woe = ln( % non-default /% default ) * 100

In [62]:
import numpy as np
# create woe formula function for train data
def WOE_train(var):
    k = train[[var,'loan_default']].groupby(var)['loan_default'].agg(['count','sum']).reset_index()
    k.columns = [var,'Count','Default']
    k['Not_default'] = k['Count'] - k['Default']
    k['Default %'] = (k['Default'] / k['Default'].sum()*100).round(4)
    k['Not_default %'] = (k['Not_default'] / k['Not_default'].sum()*100).round(4)
    k[var+'_WOE'] = np.log(k['Not_default %'] / k['Default %']).round(4)
    k = k.sort_values(by=var+'_WOE')
    return(k)

# define woe formula for test data
def WOE_test(var):
    k = test[[var,'loan_default']].groupby(var)['loan_default'].agg(['count','sum']).reset_index()
    k.columns = [var,'Count','Default']
    k['Not_default'] = k['Count'] - k['Default']
    k['Default %'] = (k['Default'] / k['Default'].sum()*100).round(4)
    k['Not_default %'] = (k['Not_default'] / k['Not_default'].sum()*100).round(4)
    k[var+'_WOE'] = np.log(k['Not_default %'] / k['Default %']).round(4)
    k = k.sort_values(by=var+'_WOE')
    return(k)

Conclusion:¶

  • The higher AUC score, the better the performance of the model at predicting 0 classes as 0 and 1 classes as 1.
  • For this case, model 2 has a better performance at predicting default from non-default

Section 4. Summary & limitation¶

For this project,

  • I did exploratory data analysis to understand the variables, the relationship between variables and target variable
  • I did feature engineering, perform weight of evidence encoding
  • I created two models, one without feature engineering, and one with feature engineering. Compare the results and performance of the two models

Limitation:

  • When performing variable transformation for training and testing data, I manually create the same variable bins for testing data based on the training data. Luckily this time, all test variables fall within the bin groups without exception. I did not consider this is the best way to perform variable transformation and would research and study more to come up with better solutions.
